{
  "texts": [
    "After all, maybe the Turing test was never about the abilities of the machine in question, but the abilities of the human capabilities to comprehend their own natural limitations.",
    "One wonders, are there any more advanced tests we could try to find out if the machines truly understand?If we think about it, the greatest accomplishments of the human species, notwithstanding our tendency for violence; our languages, our communications, our collaboration and understanding of each other, within our cultures and societies, are based on the ability to communicate our unobservable mental states, such as our vague thoughts, our beliefs and desires, to others.This distinct human property is referred to in the literature as the ''Theory of [the] Mind'' (ToM) and is widely perceived as the foundational cornerstone to human social interactions, communication, empathy, consciousness, moral judgment, and even religious beliefs.",
    "It usually develops early in human life and is so critical that its malfunctions create disorders including autism, bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, and psychopathy.",
    "Even the most ''advanced'' intellectual and social animals, such as gorillas, fall far short of humans in ToM.",
    "Is it thoughts that create our feelings or feelings that create our thoughts?"
  ]
}